Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[RadioTutorialStati: The **Radio Stations** available in the network are listed here.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[RadioTutorialVolum: Adjust the **volume up or down** to your liking.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[RadioTutorialAds]:
Don't like commercials interrupting your music?

You can **turn ads on or off** here.
Tutorials.TRIGGER[KeyboardCameraTutorial: Move the camera with the <inputAction:Camera/Move> keys.
Zoom in and out with <inputAction:Camera/Zoom[1]> and  <inputAction:Camera/Zoom[0]> or by scrolling with the mouse wheel.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[PausemenuTutorialI:
You can visit the pause menu at any time. 

To Save and Load your game.

Under Options you will find settings for Graphics, Audio, Tutorials and more.  

**The game will be paused while the menu is open.**
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[SimulationSpeedTut:
**Pausing the simulation will temporarily stop time.**

This allows you to build, plan and find solutions at your own pace. 

Once you're done, **unpause the game to resume the flow of time** so that life in the city will continue.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[UndergroundTutoria:
You can **turn the underground view on and off** here at any time.

Turning on the underground view makes it easier to build at different depths and to find connection points.

You can also use it while replacing or bulldozing roads and pipes that are built underground.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[CinematicCameraTut:
**Make a video!**

Make your camera move through your city, change the time of day as the camera moves and add camera effects.

Capture the video with your favorite software.

**This is the Timeline for your video.**

Start with the marker at the beginning of the timeline.

**Tracking your camera movement is done by placing Capture Keys to the timeline.**

Each Capture Key records the place of the camera at the moment you select the Key.

Start by moving your camera to where you want to start from and add a Capture Key.

**Capture Keys will appear here on the curve.**

This is the representation of your camera position.

**Move the Timeline marker forward.**

this is the amount of time that elapses between the Capture Keys.

**Move your camera and add your next Capture Key.**

Repeat this as many times as you want, to create the camera movement you want.

**Capture Keys can be adjusted on the curve.**

To adjust and edit your camera position and movement, you can select Capture Keys on the curve and move them.

Select the Capture Key you want to remove on the curve, the Capture Key icon will change to show a minus sign.

**Delete the Capture Key by selecting the Capture Key icon.**
**To view your timeline in a different length of time,** move the slider back and forth here.
**To preview your camera movement or view what position your camera is in a CaptureKey,** move the Timeline marker back and forth on the Timeline.

**You can use any of the Camera Effects in your video.**

Turn on the camera option you want by selecting the checkbox, adjust the effect, and **add it to your Timeline by selecting the Capture Key Icon next to the checkbox.**

**Camera effect Capture Keys will appear here on a curve.**

To make changes like moving from day to night during your camera movement.

Select and adjust the camera option you want, add the camera capture key at the beginning of the Timeline, move the Timeline marker to when you want to effect to be different and add a Capture Key with different settings.

**To play the camera movement, select play.**

This will show you the camera movement you have made, without any icons or panels on the screen.

Return normal view with <inputAction:Navigation/Back>

**To play the camera movement, select play.**

This will show you the camera movement you have made, without any icons or panels on the screen.

Return normal view with <inputAction:Navigation/Back>
Save and Load the Camera Movement and settings you have made.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[PhotoModeTutorialI:
**Take a snapshot or spend some time and delve into the art of photography.** 

You can use the default camera or fine tune it with lots of options.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[PhotoModeTutorialC:
**Build the camera you want.**

Change the sensor size, Blade Count and more.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[PhotoModeTutorialL:
**Tune your Camera Lens.**

Vignette, Bloom and others, get the effect you want.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[PhotoModeTutorialC:
**Get the colors just right.**

Bright and saturated, black and white and everything in between, make it happen here.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[PhotoModeTutorialW:
**Move the clouds and color the sky.**

Clouds not in the right place for the perfect shot or the tint of the sky not what you want? You can fix it here.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[PhotoModeTutorialE:
**Change the time of day.**

Don't wait around for the right moment in time, choose it here.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[PhotoModeTutorialA:
**Select the check box next to each feature to turn it on.**

To change the value, hover over the option and drag the arrows left or right with <inputAction:Tool/Apply>

You can also enter the value manually, using a keyboard.

**Select the check box next to each feature to turn it on.**

To change the value of the feature

Move to the value with <inputAction:Navigation/Move Horizontal>

Activate the value by selecting it with <inputAction:Tool/Apply>

**Use keyboard to change the value.**
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[PhotoModeTutorialT: Take Photo button **captures a picture without any of the UI elements and saves it to the Screenshots folder.**
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[PhotoModeTutorialH:
**Hide UI button hides all icons, panels and notifications, including the Photo Mode panel.**

This is useful for fine tuning your image composition without obstructions to the view.

**While in Hide UI mode, take a picture with** <inputAction:Shortcuts/Take Photo>

**Return to normal view with** <inputAction:Tool/Cancel[1]>

**Hide UI button hides all icons, panels and notifications, including the Photo Mode panel.**

This is useful for fine tuning your image composition without obstructions to the view.

While in Hide UI mode, **take a picture with** <inputAction:Shortcuts/Take Photo>

**Return to normal view with** <inputAction:Navigation/Back>
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[MilestoneTutorialC:
Track how your city is growing and how far you have to go to reach the next milestone.

**Milestones unlock new features, dev points and more.**
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[MapTileTutorialInt:
**Purchasing new map tiles expands the area you can build on.**

You can select tiles with <inputAction:Tool/Apply> and deselect them with <inputAction:Tool/Secondary Apply> 

To select or deselect multiple tiles at once, **hold down the button, drag and release.**

You can make your city any shape you like. **Tiles don't need to be connected, but it is easier to grow your city if they are.**

**Purchasing new map tiles expands the area you can build on.**

You can select tiles with <inputAction:Tool/Apply> and deselect them with <inputAction:Tool/Secondary Apply>

To select or deselect multiple tiles at once, **hold down the button, drag and release.**

You can make your city any shape you like. **Tiles don't need to be connected, but it is easier to grow your city if they are.**
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[AirwaysTutorialPla:
Airports are some of the largest service buildings, and need a lot of room.

**Look for a large, flat area to build your Airport on, and keep an eye on the airport airspace.**

Airspace is room for airplanes to climb after takeoff and for approaching the airport for landing.

Remember to also build road access to the Airport so that passengers and cargo can move in and out without problems.
Tutorials.TODO_OUTRO_GAMEPAD:
Well Done!

You have completed your tasks and now have the basic knowledge of how to build a city.

Going forward, more tutorials and hints will pop up to guide you on your way.

If you feel like you no longer need the guidance, **you can turn tutorials off in the pause menu.**

You can always review old tutorials by accessing the Advisor with <inputAction:Shortcuts/Advisor>.


**Would you like to continue building this city or start a new one?**
Tutorials.TRIGGER[KeyboardCameraTutorial:
Rotate the camera with <inputAction:Camera/Rotate[2]> and <inputAction:Camera/Rotate[3]> 
Tilt the camera with <inputAction:Camera/Rotate[0]> and <inputAction:Camera/Rotate[1]> 
or hold down the middle mouse button and move the mouse.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[TrainOutsideTutori: To decrease the highway traffic caused by visiting tourist and people moving into the city, **you can create Passenger Railway Lines to the outside world.**
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[LandmarksTutorialI:
**Landmarks make the city an attractive destination for tourists, and increases the happiness of citizens.**

Landmarks are somewhat expensive to upkeep. Place them thoughtfully and keep an eye on their numbers.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[VegetationTutorial:
Trees, bushes and other greenery can be used to decorate your city.

**Trees grows with the passing of time.**
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[CityInfoTutorialDe:
**Plus signs indicate an abundance of the described resource or labor force type** in your city, which increases demand for the zone type.

**Minus signs indicate a lack of the described resource or labor force type** in your city, which lowers demand for the zone type.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[SignatureBuildingT:
**These are unique buildings that unlock one by one as you fulfill requirements specific for each building.**

Once unlocked, you can build one of each of the Signature Buildings.

Building a Signature Building grants you XP.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[TourismTutorialAtt:
**Attractions are buildings with an Attractiveness value.**

These include **Parks & Recreation** buildings, and some **Signature Buildings.**
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[EducationTutorialI:
**Elementary schools provide the beginning of the education path for citizens.**

Elementary Schools provide a passive well-being bonus to nearby families with children.

**Build elementary schools in areas with families.**

Children will start attending the nearest school to their home, no matter how far it is.

**Keep in mind that if children need to travel too far to attend elementary school, it will negatively affect their families well-being.**

Schools can hold a limited amount of students, so you will need to build more schools as the population grows.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[UpgradeTutorialUpg:
Select the upgrade you want from the menu.

**Depending on the upgrade, it is added to an existing building as an extension, or placed on the side as a separate sub-building.**

Most upgrades can only be applied once to any given building, but there are some you can add multiple times.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[UpgradeTutorialSub:
**Sub-Building Upgrades can be build anywhere within the marked area.**

Sub-Buildings don't need to be connected to a road or be build on the zoning grid, they can be freely placed on any free spot inside the area.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[UpgradeTutorialPed:
**If Sub-Buildings are placed outside the zoning grid or away from the road, you will need to build Paths for Pedestrian Access.**

You can get creative and build complex areas for the service building by adding paths, landscaping and other items within the Sub-Building Area.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[UpgradeTutorialRel:
You can move individual Sub-Buildings after they have been build.

**Select the building and find the relocate icon in the info panel or find the sub-building in the main building panel and select relocate in the dropdown next to the sub-building name you want.**

You can also relocate the whole Service Building Complex with its extensions and sub-buildings by selecting the relocate icon in the main service building panel.
Tutorials.TITLE[UpgradeTutorialServiceTo: Water and Electricity to the Sub-Buildings
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[UpgradeTutorialSer:
Water, Sewage and Electricity to the Sub-Buildings are handled by the main service building.

**The pipes and electricity lines to the sub-buildings are not visible on the map.** 

Only the main building needs to be connected to a road for all the sub-buildings to receive the services.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[MapTileTutorialMap: **New map tiles will start to accrue an Upkeep Cost**. The total amount of the upkeep is determined by how much each map tile costs to purchase and how many map tiles you have already purchased. After you have purchased new map tiles, the cost will be added to the city expenses. You can view all your city expenses in the City Economy Budget panel.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[FireAndRescueTutor:
**Buildings that have been damaged but not collapsed will get repaired automatically** and the cost is taken from the building rent.

**Collapsed buildings are dealt by Disaster Response Unit**. Disaster Response Unit is an upgrade for Fire Stations, that searches for survivors in the collapsed building and clears out the rubble afterwards.

**Disaster Response Units can be imported from an Outside Connection** when the city can’t provide them.

**You can always Bulldoze Collapsed Buildings** manually to have the site checked, cleared and ready for rebuilding.
Tutorials.DISABLE_CONFIRMATION_TEXT:
Even with tutorials disabled, you can always access the information from the **Advisor.**

The Advisor offers helpful information in case you get stuck, or want more in-depth information on a feature.

Select the **?** symbol located in the top right corner of the screen to open the Advisor and browse the content.

If at some point you would like to resume the tutorials, go to the **pause menu options section to turn them on again.**

**Are you sure you want to disable tutorials?**
Tutorials.DISABLE_CONFIRMATION_TEXT_GAME:
Even with tutorials disabled, you can always access the information from the **Advisor.**

The Advisor offers helpful information in case you get stuck, or want more in-depth information on a feature.

Press <inputAction:Shortcuts/Advisor> to open the Advisor and browse the content.

If at some point you would like to resume the tutorials, go to the **pause menu options section to turn them on again.**

**Are you sure you want to disable tutorials?**
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[ConsoleHintsTutori: The controller actions are shown at the top of the screen.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[RoadsTutorialEleva: Adjusts **how much the elevation changes** with each step of adjustment.
Tutorials.LIST_REMINDER_DESCRIPTION:
When you're ready, there is a tutorial task waiting for you.

**Find the next task in the task list to continue learning how to build a city.**
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[BulldozerTutorialI:
Made a mistake? Don't worry, you can bulldoze it. 

Select the bulldozer and use

<inputAction:Tool/Apply> **to remove objects and get a refund.**

<inputAction:Shortcuts/Bulldozer> is a shortcut to activate the bulldozer at any time.

Made a mistake? Don't worry, you can bulldoze it. 

Select the bulldozer and use

<inputAction:Tool/Apply> **to remove objects and get a refund.**

<inputAction:Shortcuts/Bulldozer> is a shortcut to activate the bulldozer at any time.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[SimulationSpeedTut:
If you feel time is going by too slowly or passing by too quickly, you can **switch between three different simulation speeds.**

<inputAction:Shortcuts/Pause Simulation> is a shortcut to pause and unpause the simulation at any time.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[RoadsTutorialToolO:
**Hide UI button hides all icons, panels and notifications, including the Photo Mode panel.**

This is useful for fine tuning your image composition without obstructions to the view.

**While in Hide UI mode, take a picture with** <inputAction:Shortcuts/Take Photo>

**Return to normal view with** <inputAction:Navigation/Back>

These options can help fine-tune the shape and placement of your roads. 

**With snapping on, roads and other objects become magnetic to what snapping modes you have turned on.**

Snapping options can be turned on and off individually.

**Before you start building your roads close the Tool Options menu with** <inputAction:Tool/Cancel>
EditorTutorials.TODO_INTRO:
To help you get started with the Editor, we've prepared a series of tutorials. These will provide an overview of the Editor's features and show you where to find various controls.

**When tutorials are turned On, guides will appear as you interact with new panels in the Editor.** You can toggle tutorials On or Off using the ? icon.

You can also find all available tutorials in the Advisor panel. Each tutorial can be started from the Advisor, even if tutorials are turned Off.

**Would you like to continue with the tutorials?**
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Introduction:
**With this editor you can make maps, edit assets and import custom meshes and textures to create new assets.**

New maps that are created will be added to the custom map gallery and can then be used in game.

You can edit existing assets, and make variants of them to be used in game.

If you have made your own models to be used as assets, you can import custom geometry and textures and configure them to be used in game.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[MenuButtons]: **Buttons for the main actions you can take.** These will open their own panels to the side for more controls.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Simulation]:
**You can turn the simulation On and adjust the speed, to test your creation.** 

See how water flows on your map, how your assets function, and how everything looks under different conditions.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[CalendarAndW: Adjusting the Time, Calendar and Cloudiness slider gives you a quick look on how they affect your map and assets.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Toggles]: Variety of icons are here for actions like changing the camera mode, turning tutorials On/Off and returning to the Pause Menu.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[InfoViews]:
**Info Views will provide you a visual of where resources are and how much of them there are.** 

This is especially useful when making maps. Pollution overview can also be used to see how much pollution buildings are producing.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Workspace]:
**Workspace is the whole world area you have on your screen.** 

The map controls and all the assets you have added or imported can be found here.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[ImportingAss: You can import your own 3D models and textures to be configured for in game use.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[ProjectRoot]: Select the main folder where all your projects files and sub folders are located in.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[SelectedAsse: Select the subfolder where the asset files you want to import are located in.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[SelectTempla:
Select a similar asset to what you want to do as a template. This will copy the properties and layout of that asset to yours.

You can also start from an empty template to define your asset from scratch.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Import]:
Select to start importing files to the template.

**This process may take a short while.**
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[ModifyingThe:
With the terrain tools you can build and modify the ground to make your own playable map for the game.

**The entire map is the green area in your workspace and the marked area in the middle is the default starting area.**
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[TerrainTools:
Here are the tools to paint the ground to different shapes and heights. 

**When you have selected a tool, options for it will be shown at the bottom.**
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Heightmaps]:
There are two different Heightmaps. The main Heightmap is for the playable map area, which is shown as a green plane, and the World heightmap is for the area outside your map. Area that can only be seen as the background.

Heightmaps are grayscale images that can be used to create the grounds shape and height of the terrain. White areas will be the highest points and black areas the lowest points.

You can make a heightmap in any software that can save the image in the appropriate format.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[HeightScale]:
**The Height Scale number defines how high the highest point can be on your map, in meters.**

If you have made a heightmap image the white parts will be at the number you set. This will also set how high the ground can be build in game. 

Default Height is 4096.000 and max is 10000.000
**Note:** Extreme heights can cause grounds textures to stretch beyond what looks nice.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[ImportHeight:
Before you can import an image to be used as a heightmap, **you need to place the image in the game folder named Heightmaps.**

**The heightmap must be in 4096x4096 pixels, grayscale image with 16 bit channel depth, in .png format.**

When you select Import Heightmap all the images in that folder are shown and are available to be used. Select the one you want and click load.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[ExportHeight:
**You can save your current terrain as a Heightmap image for editing or future importing.**

Give it a name to create a new Heightmap or select an existing file to overwrite it.

Exported Heightmaps can be found in the Heightmaps folder for later use.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[ImportingAnd:
The same rules that apply to the main Heightmap also apply to the Worldmap image. See the previous steps for more details.

**The Worldmap will extend outside the map area and provide the view of the land beyond your map. It will not affect the map area.**

**Note:** It's good practise to save your progress often and have a way to go back to a previous point. It's also a good idea to export different versions of your heightmaps.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[SculptingThe:
**To be able to sculpt the Worldmap area you will need to first import a Worldmap image.**

After you have loaded the image you can work on the area with the terrain tools.
 
If there are abrupt height differences at the edge of map, you can sculpt the edge area with the terrain tools.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[AddingObject:
Objects are models that are used in game or that you have created.

You can place object listed below to your workspace for propping or to be included in a map.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Search]: You can search object by name or keyword, and apply filters to narrow down the results.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Filter]: To view Specific types of assets, select one or more from the list to see only the selected types of assets.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Categories]: All available objects can also be found listed in the menu divided into categories.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[ThumbnailSli:
Slider for object thumbnail size.

Slide right for a larger thumbnail and left for a list view.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Favorite]:
**Select the star next an objects to find it quicker next time.**

Selecting will favorite the asset and show a star next to it. All stared objects are found at the top of the list when you have All categories selected.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Bulldozer]: Bulldozer is for deleting objects in your workspace.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[ToolMode]: Turn your prefered way of selecting objects On or Off.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[UndergroundM: Find things placed underground to delete.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Theme]:
**Selecting a theme for your map will determine the default style of objects in game.**

The style of objects like roads and road decals, lights and trees along the roads and also the look of the traffic lights and bus stops. Default theme for zoning and signature buildings.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[StartingTile:
**Starting Tiles are the area of the map that is open to be build on from the start of the game.**

Default is to have the middle 9 tiles open in a 3x3 square. You can choose any tiles and as many as you like. 

Select with <inputAction:Tool/Apply> and deselect with <inputAction:Tool/Secondary Apply>
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[PreviewImage:
**Preview image is for showcasing your map.** To give a nice overview of what your map is like. 

Preview Image is a RGB color mode, 8 bits/channel, 687 x 384 pixels in .png format
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[ThumbnailIma:
**Thumbnail Image is to identify your map** when selecting a new map at the start of a new game.

RGB color mode, 8 bits/channel, 200x200 pixels in .png format
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Checklist]:
For the map to function properly in the game, certain essential elements must be included.

Then a few things that are nice to have.

**The checklist will show you what you have placed in your map so you can make sure your map will work.**
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[WindSettings:
**Control the wind direction with the slider. Arrows are shown on the map for visual aid of the wind direction.**

Wind direction can be important when designing a map with great elevation differences. Wind direction can affect where good areas are for industrial zoning or where wind power stations are most efficient to place.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[ClimateSetti:
**Climate settings include setting for what global area the map is situated in.**

These are setting that affect how cold or warm the map is and what position the sun is in, which affect how long the days and nights are.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Water]:
**Water Settings are for all types of water that are present in the map.**

Water for scenic purposes like lakes and ponds. Larger water ways like rivers and sea for boat and ship traffic. Most importantly water for citizens use.

**Note:** For the map to work in game you must include at least one surface or groundwater source where the city can get its water supply.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[Resources]:
**Resources are materials found in the ground.**

Materials like water that the city needs for its citizens and companies to live and function.

Other materials are used by industries, to cultivate the land or harvest the materials found there.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[ResourcesToo:
**With the resource tools you can paint the area that will contain the selected material.**

When a tool is selected Brush Tool Options are shown at the bottom.

Different brush shapes are useful when painting mountains and other natural features with textured surfaces. Size, Strength and angel help with detailing the areas.
EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[ImportTextur:
Texture images for resources work the same as the heightmaps and need to be located in the same folder. The game folder named Heightmaps.

So before you import images, place the texture in the Heightmaps folder.

**The images must be 4096x4096 pixels, grayscale image with 16 bit channel depth, in .png format.**

When you select Import Heightmap all the images in that folder are shown and available to be used. Select the one you want and click load.
Tutorials.TITLE[RoadServicesTutorialRemo: Placing and Removing Signs and Decorations
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[RoadsTutorialTwoLa:
The Two-lane Road is a basic road with two lanes, one in each direction, with street lamps on one side. 

It is easy to build with, but it can only support a low amount of traffic.

**When selecting a road, keep an eye on the information panel.**
It will show you how much the road costs to build and maintain, and how much electricity the built-in utility network can handle.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[ElectricityFlowTut:
**Electricity info view shows an overlay of electricity flow throughout the city, to help you spot weaknesses and solve problems.**

Electricity panel also shows detailed information about the performance of the electricity grid, conditions that affect it and where your electricity plants are located.

EditorTutorials.DESCRIPTION[EditorPhotoM:
**Take a snapshot or spend some time and delve into the art of photography.** 

You can use the default camera or fine tune it with lots of options.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[CityInfoTutorialCi:
**You can activate and deactivate policies any time.**

Some policies have adjustment sliders to fine-tune their effect.

Select a policy to see what its effects are.

More policies are unlocked as you reach certain milestones and build and upgrade certain city service buildings.

Change the sensor size, Blade Count and more.

**Tune your Camera Lens.**

Vignette, Bloom and others, get the effect you want.

**Get the colors just right.**

Bright and saturated, black and white and everything in between, make it happen here.

Clouds not in the right place for the perfect shot or the tint of the sky not what you want? You can fix it here.

**Change the time of day.**

Don't wait around for the right moment in time, choose it here.

Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[SewageTutorialConn:
**If your Sewage Outlet is already built connected to a road, you're all set**  The Sewage Outlet is connected to the roads utility network.

**If your Sewage Outlet isn't connected to a road, you'll need to do so.**

Find the nearest road that has the built in utility network.

Sewage piping will be highlighted while the Sewage Pipe is selected and Water & Sewage info view is active.

**Connect the Sewage Outlet to the road utility network with the Sewage Pipe.**

**Note:** Highways don't have built in utility networks, and you can't connect to an individual building's pipe connection.
Tutorials.DESCRIPTION[ProductionTutorial:
The production tab shows you how much your city is producing.

**You can view production from materials, material goods, and immaterial goods.**

**Expand the categories and select a resource to see the production chain of that resource.**

**Raw Material** are resources you can either grow, mine or harvest by building the appropriate industrial facilities.

**Processed Goods** are resources that can be made from the raw materials like Plastics, Food and refined materials just as Timber.  You can get these resources by zoning land for industrial use.

**Immaterial Goods** are resources that take processed goods and turn them in to things like Entertainment and Software.

**Shows all the possible ways the selected resource can be obtained and how it can be used to produce goods and immaterial goods.**

This can be useful for planning production of resources and understanding what is needed in the city for the production to flourish. You can  map out what raw materials are used in different  production lines to be turned in to processed goods and then where those goods are used to make immaterial goods.

**Note:** the selected raw material or produced good is in the middle grey box.

**On the left** of the grey box is where the raw material or goods can be acquired from.

**Blue labels** indicate that you can build industrial facilities that produce the selected material or zone for the type of companies that produce the selected good.

**Red labels** show that the material or good can be imported if there is more demand for it in the city then is being produced.

**On the right** side of the grey box is all the places where the resource can go and what can be produced from it.

**Yellow labels** are the facilities that use the resource to produce further goods and next to them the product they make. 

**Green labels** indicate that the material or product can be exported to outside locations if there is more produced then the city needs.

**This chart will show the live data of the production chain.**

The amounts your city is producing or importing the selected material or good. Where it's being used and how much of it.

This will fluctuate and adapt to what is going on in your city.

**Note** The grey bar in the middle is the selected material or good, with a label next to it of the total amount available in your city.

**On the left** is where the material or goods are coming from and how much of it is flowing in.

This can be from production in your city (blue) or from importing (red) or both, they come together at the grey line that indicates the total amount at the moment in your city.

**On the right** side are the places where the material or good is going and how much of it is going to each place.

**Yellow labels** show the production facilities that receive the material or good and how much they use. With a further label on the right showing what they have produced from that material and how much of it.

**Green labels** show that there is a surplus of that material or good at that junkion and it's being exported to an outside connection.
WhatsNew.BEACH_PROPERTIES_P1_DESCRIPTION:
New Waterfront Zone for European Theme gives your city a touch of Southern European coastal city charm, and 
New iconic fences around the yards help tie the buildings together with the region's style.

New Waterfront Zone for the North American Theme brings an atmosphere of the Florida coastline to your cities, and new swimming pools in the backyards liven up the neighborhoods.
WhatsNew.BEACH_PROPERTIES_P2_DESCRIPTION:
North American signature buildings take inspiration from the sun-kissed Florida beaches and villas. 

Spanish styled villas can be found from the European themed signature buildings. 
All these new luxurious signature buildings are sure way to increase the sunshine in your city!
WhatsNew.BEACH_PROPERTIES_P3_TITLE: It's time to face the palm trees!
WhatsNew.BEACH_PROPERTIES_P3_DESCRIPTION: In the Vegetation menu is a collection of new Palm Trees to bring a cool ocean breeze and relaxed beach vibes to your city!
